Wang and Abramenko (2000) used Huairou vector magnetograms to analyse the emerging AR 7321 during three days. They found that
the total positive (negative) electric current grew simultaneously and linearly with the increase of the total positive (negative) flux;
a linear extrapolation to the zero flux gave a non-vanishing total current, which may indicate that the photospheric magnetic field is not force-free;
the Î± parameter, which characterises the twist of the flux for the entire AR remained nearly constant during the emergence.

The magnetic field of an active region is dominated by its sunspots. So, for the region to decay any spots that are present must be removed. Overall, the evolution of the photospheric magnetic field is described by the MHD Induction equation. 1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\partial B} \over {\partial t}} = \nabla \times ({\bf{v}} \times {\bf{B}}) + \eta {\nabla ^2}{\bf{B}},$$\end{document} where Î· is the ohmic magnetic diffusivity. The first term on the right-hand side describes changes to the magnetic field as it is advected by plasma flows and the second term on the right-hand side describes changes as the magnetic field diffuses through the plasma. Which of these terms dominates is determined through the ratio known as the magnetic Reynolds number: 2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Re _m} \equiv {{\nu \ell } \over \eta },$$\end{document} where Î½ is the velocity and â is the lengthscale. If âm âª 1 then the diffusion term dominates and the plasma motions are not important. The diffusion timescale for a sunspot with a length-scale of 3000 km and Î· = 300 m2 sâ1 is â¼ 1000 years. If âm â« 1 then advection dominates the evolution of the magnetic field. In the latter case, the magnetic energy density of the magnetic field \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
