Limb-to limb signed magnetic flux measurements of slowly-evolving decaying regions were used by Karachik et al. (2010) to determine the mean inclination Î³ of magnetic vector in the polarities of these bipolar ARs from the central meridian distance (CMD) where each polarity reached maximum: Bâ¥(CMD) = B0 cos(CMD â Î³), where B0 is the flux along the axis of the flux tube. The magnetic field measurements were done over a rectangular area containing the decaying ARs. There is no mention of background flux subtraction nor of the size of the box (whether it was of constant area or adjusted to the increasing dimensions of the diffusing AR), which can very well influence the measured flux decay rate, i.e., from a small box flux is diffusing out, while a box of varying size includes a varying amount of âbackgroundâ field. When an AR emerges into a pre-existing monopolar area (plage field), a polarity imbalance of the bipole can develop as the emerging bipoleâs polarity opposite to that of the background field will cancel with the latter. With these potential limitations, Table 3 shows two of the decaying ARs for which flux measurements, compactness on consecutive rotations were made. Compactness was characterised by 3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
